        "URL": "data:text/html;charset=utf-8,%3C!doctype%20html%3E%0A%3Chtml%20lang%3D%22%22%3E%0A%3Chead%3E%0A%20%20%3Cmeta%20charset%3D%22utf-8%22%3E%0A%20%20%3Ctitle%3EWhat's%20Hysteresis%3F%3C%2Ftitle%3E%0A%3C%2Fhead%3E%0A%3Cbody%3E%0A%3Cbody%3E%0A%0A%3Ch1%3EWhat's%20Hysteresis%3F%3C%2Fh1%3E%0A%3Cp%3E%0A%0AWebster's%20Seventh%20New%20Collegiate%20Dictionary%20tells%20us%3A%0A%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdl%3E%0A%3Cdt%3Ehys-ter-e-sis%3A%20%0A%3C%2Fdt%3E%3Cdd%3E%3Cem%3En%3C%2Fem%3E%20%5BNL%2C%20fr.%20Gk%20%3Cem%3Ehysteresis%3C%2Fem%3E%0Ashortcoming%2C%20fr.%20%3Cem%3Ehysterein%3C%2Fem%3E%20to%20be%20late%2C%20fall%20short%2C%20fr.%0A%3Cem%3Ehysteros%3C%2Fem%3E%20later%5D%0A%3Cp%3Ea%20retardation%20of%20the%20effect%20when%20the%20forces%20acting%20upon%20a%20body%0Aare%20changed%20(as%20if%20from%20viscosity%20or%20internal%20friction)%3B%20%3Cem%3Eesp%3C%2Fem%3E%3A%0Aa%20lagging%20in%20the%20values%20of%20resulting%20magnetization%20in%20a%20magnetic%20material%0A(as%20iron)%20due%20to%20a%20changing%20magnetizing%20force.%20%20%0A-%3Cstrong%3Ehys-ter-et-ic%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20%3Cem%3Eadj%3C%2Fem%3E%0A%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdd%3E%3C%2Fdl%3E%20%0A%0AThere%20seems%20to%20be%20no%20%3Ca%20href%3D%22etymological_def.html%22%3Eetymological%3C%2Fa%3E%0Alink%20between%20hysteresis%20and%20either%20hysterical%20(fr.%20L%20%3Cem%3Ehystericus%3C%2Fem%3E%0Aof%20the%20womb)%20or%20history%20(fr.%20Gk%2C%20inquiry%2C%20history%2C%0Afr.%20%3Cem%3Ehistor%2C%20istor%3C%2Fem%3E%20knowing%2C%20learned).%20%20This%20is%20too%20bad%2C%20as%0Athere%20are%20scientific%20connections%20to%20both%20words.%20%0A(There%20is%20no%20link%2C%20scientific%20or%20etymological%2C%20to%20histolysis%2C%20the%0Abreakdown%20of%20bodily%20tissues%2C%20or%20to%20blood.)%3Cp%3E%0A%0AHysteresis%20represent%20the%20%3Cem%3Ehistory%3C%2Fem%3E%20dependence%20of%20physical%20systems.%0AIf%20you%20push%20on%20something%2C%20it%20will%20yield%3A%20when%20you%20release%2C%0Adoes%20it%20spring%20back%20completely%3F%20%20If%20it%20doesn't%2C%20it%20is%20exhibiting%20%0Ahysteresis%2C%20in%20some%20broad%20sense.%20%20The%20term%20is%20most%20commonly%20applied%2C%0Aas%20Webster%20implies%2C%20to%20magnetic%20materials%3A%20as%20the%20external%20field%20with%0Athe%20signal%20from%20the%20microphone%20is%20turned%20off%2C%20the%20little%20magnetic%20domains%20%0Ain%20the%20tape%20don't%20return%20to%20their%20original%20configuration%0A(by%20design%2C%20otherwise%20your%20record%20of%20the%20music%20would%20disappear!)%0AHysteresis%20happens%20in%20lots%20of%20other%20systems%3A%20if%20you%20place%20a%20large%0Aforce%20on%20your%20fork%20while%20cutting%20a%20tough%20piece%20of%20meat%2C%20it%20doesn't%0Aalways%20return%20to%20its%20original%20shape%3A%20the%20shape%20of%20the%20fork%20depends%0Aon%20its%20history.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%0A%0A%3Cimg%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%0A%0AHysteresis%20loops%20happen%20when%20you%20%0Arepeatedly%20wiggle%20the%20system%20back%20and%20forth%20(cycle%20the%20field%20up%20and%20down).%0AThe%20magnetization%20of%20a%20tape%20will%20%60%60lag%20behind''%20as%20the%20field%20sweeps%0Aup%20and%20as%20it%20sweeps%20down.%20%20The%20memory%20in%20the%20tape%20is%20the%20magnetization%20%0Aremaining%20as%20the%20field%20is%20released%20to%20zero%20from%20a%20large%20value.%0AIn%20magnetic%20tapes%2C%20this%20lag%20is%20%0A%3Ca%20href%3D%22ReturnPointMemory.html%22%3Erepeatable%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%20%0Athe%20shape%20of%20the%20loop%20after%20the%20first%20cycle%20is%20roughly%20%0Athe%20same%20as%20it%20is%20after%20many%20cycles.%20%20(This%20is%20convenient%20for%20doing%20%0Amultiple%20recordings%20on%20the%20same%20tape.)%20%20This%20is%20not%20true%20of%20many%20other%20%0Asystems%3A%20forks%2C%20for%20example%2C%20after%20being%20bent%20back%20and%20forth%20many%20times%2C%20%0Awill%20actually%20become%20stiffer%20(%60%60work%20hardening'')%20and%20then%20break.%0AThere%20is%20a%20class%20of%20metals%20(called%20%0A%3Ca%20href%3D%22https%3A%2F%2Fsethna.lassp.cornell.edu%2FTweed%2FWhat_Are_Martensites.html%22%3E%0Ashape%20memory%20alloys%3C%2Fa%3E)%20that%20can%20be%20bent%20or%0Astretched%20plastically%20large%20distances%20back%20and%20forth%20many%20times%20without%20%0Awork%20hardening%3A%20this%20%3Cem%3Esuperelastic%3C%2Fem%3E%20behavior%20is%20only%20one%20property%0Aof%20these%20interesting%20materials.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%0A%0AMany%20hysteretic%20systems%20make%20%3Ca%20href%3D%22noise.html%22%3Escreeching%20noises%3C%2Fa%3E%20%0Aas%20they%20respond%20to%20their%20external%20load%20(hence%2C%20the%20natural%20connection%20%0Awith%20%3Cem%3Ehysteria%3C%2Fem%3E).%0A%0A%3Ca%20href%3D%22references.html%22%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22references.html%22%3EReferences%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%0A%0AMore%20information%3A%0A%3Cul%3E%0A%3Cli%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22authors.html%22%3EAuthors%3C%2Fa%3E%0A%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22hysteresis.html%22%3EHysteresis%3C%2Fa%3E%0A%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22noise.html%22%3ENoise%20in%20Hysteresis%3C%2Fa%3E%0A%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22https%3A%2F%2Fsethna.lassp.cornell.edu%2Fhysteresis%2FReturnPointMemory.html%22%3E%0AReturn%20Point%20Memory%3C%2Fa%3E%0A%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22https%3A%2F%2Fsethna.lassp.cornell.edu%2Fhysteresis%2FHysteresisCriticalPoint.html%22%3E%0AThe%20Critical%20Point%3C%2Fa%3E%0A%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22https%3A%2F%2Fsethna.lassp.cornell.edu%2Fhysteresis%2FEpsilonExpansion.html%22%3E%0AThe%20Epsilon%20Expansion%3C%2Fa%3E%0A%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%0A%0A%3Chr%3E%0A%0A%3Ch1%3ELinks%20Back%3C%2Fh1%3E%0A%3Cdl%20compact%3D%22%22%3E%0A%3Cdt%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lassp.cornell.edu%2FLASSP_Science.html%22%3E%0A%3Cimg%3E%20%0AEntertaining%20Science%3C%2Fa%3E%20done%20at%3C%2Fdt%3E%0A%3Cdt%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%22http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lassp.cornell.edu%2F%22%3E%0A%3Cimg%3E%20LASSP.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdt%3E%0A%3C%2Fdl%3E%0A%0A%3Chr%3E%0ALast%20modified%3A%20June%2030%2C%201994%3Cp%3E%0A%3Ca%20href%3D%22https%3A%2F%2Fsethna.lassp.cornell.edu%2